\section{Dual-Track Audio Synthesis}
\label{sec:tts}
The final annotated text scripts were converted into dual-track audio using an advanced Text-to-Speech (TTS) model, \texttt{gpt-4o-mini-tts} and \texttt{gemini-2.5-pro-tts}. Each channel corresponds to one speaker. By precisely controlling the single speaker actions, we synthesized realistic interactive audio containing speech overlaps and silences of varying durations. We accurately record the conversation timestamps, the time and duration of each interaction event.
\section{Real-World Dataset Curation and Annotation}
\label{sec:realworld}
\subsection{Real-World Human-Machine (RW-HM) Dataset}
To capture nuanced interaction dynamics, we curated a Real-World Human-Machine (RW-HM) dataset through structured, goal-oriented conversations. The objective was to move beyond simple free-form dialogue and to systematically elicit both successful (\textit{Good Cases}) and failed (\textit{Bad Cases}) examples of specific interaction phenomena. This process created a balanced dataset crucial for training a reward model sensitive to the subtleties of conversational fluency.
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Data Collection Process:} We recruited and trained seven fluent English-speaking participants to act as expert testers. Their task was to engage in conversations with SOTA models and deliberately engineer scenarios corresponding to four predefined interaction behaviors. For each behavior, participants were instructed to aim for a roughly 1:1 ratio of successful to failed outcomes.

 \item \textbf{SOTA Models Used:} The interactions were conducted with the latest voice-enabled versions of leading dialogue systems: \textbf{GPT-4o} (voice mode), \textbf{Gemini Live}, and \textbf{Doubao}.
 \item \textbf{Targeted Interaction Behaviors:} Participants were trained to understand and provoke four key behaviors:
 \begin{enumerate}
 \item \textbf{Standard Response:} Assessing the timeliness, relevance, and accuracy of the model's reply following a complete user query.
 \item \textbf{Intra-turn Pause:} Testing the model's patience during a natural pause within a user's utterance, with the goal of provoking either a correct wait or an incorrect \textit{Inappropriate Barge-in}.
 \item \textbf{Listener Backchannel:} Testing the model's ability to correctly process short, non-competitive listener cues (e.g., "uh-huh," "okay") during its own long utterance. The aim was to elicit either a robust continuation (correct) or an \textit{Overly Deferential Ceding} error (incorrect).
 \item \textbf{Competitive Interruption:} Testing the model's floor-taking mechanism by having the user attempt to stop the model mid-speech with a new, substantive command, in order to provoke either a \textit{Successful Interruption} or an \textit{Ignored Interruption}.
 \end{enumerate}
 \item \textbf{Participant Guidance and Protocol:} Participants were provided with a detailed instruction document that defined each target behavior and gave explicit strategies for creating both "Good Case" and "Bad Case" examples. An example is below:

 \begin{quote}
 ``In the following conversation, your task is to interact with an AI assistant. For this session, we want to test its ability to handle interruptions. Whenever you have a follow-up question, a correction, or a new idea, please feel free to interrupt the AI assistant, even while it is speaking.

 \textbf{To create a `Good Case`}: Interrupt with a clear, new command. The AI should immediately stop its current task and address your new command.

 \textbf{To create a `Bad Case`}: Attempt the same type of interruption. If the AI ignores you and continues speaking, you have successfully created a failed sample. Our goal is to collect both types of scenarios.''
 \end{quote}

 \item \textbf{Annotation:} After completing a session, participants logged the interaction with a unique ID, context, `Interaction Type`, timestamped transcriptions, and a `Quality Label`.
 \item \textbf{Case:} An example annotation case is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:annotation_case}.
\end{itemize}
