\section{Limitations} 
The primary limitation of our study is that most results are derived from a controlled synthetic testbed with relatively small models, which may raise concerns about practical relevance. This reflects an inherent trade-off: narrowing the problem scope enables rigorous and well-controlled analysis, but inevitably reduces realism. While large-scale practical benchmarks are abundant, they often make it difficult to isolate the source of generalization behavior. Our approach therefore prioritizes control and interpretability over scale.
To partially address this limitation, we validate key findings on training data properties using math datasets on 7B-scale models and relate our RL observations to recent theoretical developments. Moreover, sequential optimization itself constitutes a broad class of real-world tasks, and path-based data is closely connected to reasoning and mathematical problem solving.
