\subsection{Case Study}
Figure~\ref{fig:case_study} compares the search trajectories of Qwen3-8B before and after CW-GRPO training on a factual question regarding John I. Jenkins’s tenure start. The untrained model issues only a single query fails to distinguish between the election year and the actual commencement of his term, leading to an incorrect answer based on this temporal confusion.
In contrast, the CW-GRPO trained model adopts a qualitatively different strategy by issuing multiple parallel queries in the first round. This expanded search coverage allows the agent to recall a broader set of documents, including explicit evidence that Jenkins’s term began in 2005. This case illustrates that CW-GRPO not only improves retrieval utility through parallelization but also strengthens the agent’s resistance to distractor evidence. By learning to prioritize direct answer-bearing evidence over superficially relevant but misleading signals, the model achieves more robust and grounded search-based decision making.
